{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496701"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:53:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:53:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1403"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1403"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.06,0.08,0.48,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1403"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115564"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1403"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1403"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97567"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1787"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1955"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15664"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49203"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115564"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of persistent palpitations. He has never had these symptoms before. The day before, he attended a wedding where he consumed approximately 19 standard drinks of alcohol. He is a manager at an IT company and has recently experienced significant work-related stress. He is otherwise in good health and takes no medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination he appears well. His temperature is 36.5\u00b0C, pulse is 90/min and irregularly irregular, respiratory rate is 13/min, and blood pressure is 130/60 mmHg. Examination reveals no other abnormalities. An ECG is performed, showing no P-waves. An echocardiogram shows no abnormalities. One hour later, a repeat ECG shows normal P waves followed by normal QRS complexes. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous adenosine","Intravenous metoprolol","Apixaban therapy","Outpatient Holter monitoring","Discharge with GP follow-up"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient initially presented with what was presumed to be new-onset symptomatic atrial fibrillation. In the younger person with no history of heart disease and a presumably structurally normal heart, this can be triggered by excessive alcohol or caffeine consumption, commonly known as \u0027holiday heart syndrome\u0027. The arrhythmia has self-terminated, as evidenced by the return of normal P waves and QRS complexes on the repeat ECG. In such cases, conservative management is the appropriate approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile controlling rate and/or rhythm, as well as providing anticoagulation (according to the CHA2DS2-VA score), are key therapeutic principles in atrial fibrillation, the patient\u0027s spontaneous conversion to sinus rhythm and a CHA2DS2-VA score of 0 warrant further observation rather than any immediate medical or electrophysiological intervention. If the tachycardia had not improved spontaneously, a beta-blocker could be considered in the acute setting to control the heart rate rapidly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge with GP follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. The patient should be advised to avoid excessive alcohol consumption and manage stress. A follow-up with a GP will ensure monitoring for any recurrence of symptoms and further evaluation if necessary. As well, there should be additional investigations for causes such as hyperthyroidism, electrolyte imbalances, and obstructive sleep apnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous adenosine\u003C/strong\u003E is used for the acute termination of certain types of supraventricular tachycardia, not for atrial fibrillation. It is not indicated here as the arrhythmia has already resolved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous metoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered for rate control in persistent atrial fibrillation, but it is unnecessary in this case as the arrhythmia has resolved and the patient\u0027s heart rate is within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is used for anticoagulation in patients with atrial fibrillation who are at risk of thromboembolism. This patient has no structural heart disease or persistent atrial fibrillation, so anticoagulation is not indicated at this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOutpatient Holter monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E could be useful if there is suspicion of intermittent arrhythmias, but given the clear trigger and resolution of symptoms, it is not immediately necessary. Follow-up with a GP would be a better option to determine what type of further monitoring is required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atrial fibrillation can be triggered by excessive alcohol consumption, often referred to as \u0027holiday heart syndrome\u0027.","In cases of self-terminating atrial fibrillation with no underlying structural heart disease, conservative management and follow-up are appropriate."],"references":["Manning WJ, Singer DE, Lip GY. Atrial fibrillation: Anticoagulant therapy to prevent thromboembolism. In: Zimetbaum PJ, Kasner SE, Knight BP,Saperia GM.; UpToDate. [Internet]. Waltham (MA): UpToDate Inc; 2020 [updated 2020 Oct 27; cited 2021 Mar 07]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/atrial-fibrillation-anticoagulant-therapy-to-prevent-thromboembolism","Jain A, Yelamanchili VS, Brown KN, et al. Holiday Heart Syndrome. In: StatPearls [online]. Updated 2024 Jan 16]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537185/","Andrade JG, Deyell MW, Bennett R, Macle L. Assessment and management of asymptomatic atrial fibrillation. Heart. 2024 Apr 15;110(9):675-682. doi: 10.1136/heartjnl-2023-322428. PMID: 37507214. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37507214/","NHFA CSANZ Atrial Fibrillation Guideline Working Group; Brieger D, Amerena J, Attia J, Bajorek B, Chan KH, Connell C, Freedman B, Ferguson C, Hall T, Haqqani H, Hendriks J, Hespe C, Hung J, Kalman JM, Sanders P, Worthington J, Yan TD, Zwar N. National Heart Foundation of Australia and the Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Australian Clinical Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Atrial Fibrillation 2018. Heart Lung Circ. 2018 Oct;27(10):1209-1266. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30077228/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97567"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1403"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97567"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T13:16:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T13:18:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1403"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115564"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"